'''Michael Charles Brantley, Jr.''' (born May 15, 1987) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[outfielder]] with the [[Cleveland Indians]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He is the son of former MLB player and coach [[Mickey Brantley]].

After starring for the [[Fort Pierce Central High School]] baseball team, the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] selected Brantley in the [[2005 MLB Draft]]. After the 2008 season, Brantley was traded to the Indians along with other [[prospect (sports)|prospects]] for [[C.C. Sabathia]]. He made his MLB debut with the Indians in 2009. In 2014, Brantley was named an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|MLB All-Star]] and he won the [[Silver Slugger Award]].

==Early life==
Brantley was born in [[Bellevue, Washington]]. His father, [[Mickey Brantley]], played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB), and was a member of the [[Seattle Mariners]] at the time Michael was born. Michael was raised in [[Port St. Lucie, Florida]].<ref name=kepner/> Starting at age 7, Brantley played in Southwestern Port St. Lucie [[Little League Baseball]].<ref name=littleleague/> When Mickey worked as the [[coach (baseball)#Hitting coach|hitting coach]] for the [[New York Mets]] in 1999, Michael got to spend time around the Mets.<ref name=kepner/>

Brantley attended [[Central High School (Fort Pierce, Florida)|Central High School]] in [[Fort Pierce, Florida]], where he played for the baseball and golf teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/sports/mlb/mlb-fort-pierce-central-grad-michael-brantley-is-having-his-best-season-yet_42695577|title=MLB: Fort Pierce Central grad Michael Brantley is having his best season yet|work=TCP|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2011/04/five_questions_with_indians_le.html|title=Five Questions with ... Indians left fielder Michael Brantley|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> In his senior year for the baseball team, he had a .595 [[batting average]], scored 22 [[run (baseball)|runs]], recorded 12 [[runs batted in]] and 32 [[stolen base]]s.<ref name=littleleague/>

==Professional career==

===Milwaukee Brewers===
The [[Milwaukee Brewers]] selected Brantley in the seventh round, with the 205th overall selection, of the [[2005 Major League Baseball Draft|2005 MLB Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prosportstransactions.com/baseball/DraftTrades/2005-1-10.htm|title=2005 Major League Baseball Draft, Rounds 1&ndash;10 &ndash; Pro Sports Transactions.|work=prosportstransactions.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> After he signed with the Brewers, Brantley played for their [[Rookie-level]] affiliates, the [[Helena Brewers]] of the [[Pioneer League (baseball)|Pioneer League]] and [[Arizona Brewers]] of the [[Arizona League]]. He batted .347 with 14 stolen bases in 44 games for Arizona,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=a15ea7ec|title=2005 AZL Brewers|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> and .324 in 10 games for Helena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=eb05d88c|title=2005 Helena Brewers|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

The Brewers assigned Brantley to the [[West Virginia Power]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]] in 2006. He batted .300 with 24 stolen bases in 108 games for West Virginia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=81fcba27|title=2006 West Virginia Power|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, Brantley began the season with West Virginia. After batting .335 in 56 games,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=9fabd283|title=2007 West Virginia Power|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> the Brewers promoted Brantley to the [[Huntsville Stars]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Southern League (baseball)|Southern League]], where he batted .251 in 59 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=57df55fc|title=2007 Huntsville Stars|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Playing for Huntsville in 2008, Brantley had a .319 batting average with four home runs, 40 RBIs, and 28 stolen bases.<ref name=sabathia>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/blogs/sports/32000694.html|title=Brantley completes Sabathia deal|author=Tom Haudricourt|work=jsonline.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

===Cleveland Indians===
The Brewers traded Brantley to the [[Cleveland Indians]] on October 3, 2008, as the [[player to be named later]] (PTNBL) in the July 7 transaction where the Brewers acquired [[C.C. Sabathia]] for [[Matt LaPorta]], [[Zach Jackson]], and Rob Bryson.<ref name=sabathia/><ref name=kepner>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/10/sports/baseball/clevelands-brantley-succeeds-at-the-plate-with-help-from-his-father.html?_r=0 |last=Kepner |first=Tyler |title=A Paternal Touch Yields a Smooth Swing|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 10, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/07/the_cleveland_indians_were_for.html|title=How Michael Brantley, once a 'player to be named later,' made the Cleveland Indians winners of the CC Sabathia trade|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref> The list of choices for the PTNBL was narrowed down to Brantley and [[Taylor Green]]. The Indians and Brewers agreed that if the Brewers reached the 2008 [[MLB postseason]], the Indians could make the choice. Since the Brewers made the playoffs, the Indians got to choose, and they chose Brantley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.indians.mlb.com/news/article/3586886/|title=Brantley completes deal for Tribe|work=Cleveland Indians|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/07/the_cleveland_indians_were_for.html|title=How Michael Brantley, once a 'player to be named later,' made the Cleveland Indians winners of the CC Sabathia trade|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref>

[[File:Michael Brantley on July 16, 2011.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Brantley in 2011]]
Brantley played for the [[Columbus Clippers]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[International League]] in 2009. He hit .267 for the Clippers. When major league rosters expanded on September 1, the Indians promoted Brantley to the major leagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2009/09/cleveland_indians_expected_to_1.html|title=Cleveland Indians promote Michael Brantley and Jose Veras from Class AAA Columbus|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Brantley reached base safely in his first eight games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/sports/no-headline-spt_brantley2|title=Fort Pierce Central grad Michael Brantley is a hit with Cleveland|work=TCP|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Near the end of the 2009 season, he replaced the injured [[Grady Sizemore]] in center field. In his time there, he hit .313 with 11 RBIs in 28 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2010/02/michael_brantley_not_taking_hi.html|title=Michael Brantley not taking his shot at the Cleveland Indians lineup for granted|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Due to an injury to [[Russell Branyan]], Brantley opened the 2010 season with Cleveland, starting in [[left field]] on [[Opening Day]]. When the Indians activated Branyan on April 19, Brantley, who had batted 5-for-32, was optioned to Columbus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2010/04/cleveland_indians_option_micha.html|title=Cleveland Indians option Michael Brantley to Class AAA Columbus; prepare to activate Russell Branyan|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Brantley batted .315 in 59 games for Columbus, and was recalled to the major leagues on July 4 after an injury to [[Shin-Soo Choo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2010/07/tribe_keep_spot_warm_for_carlo.html|title=Michael Brantley brings confidence from Columbus stint to the Tribe: Indians Insider|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> After batting 11-for-70 with one home run in 26 games in his second stint with the 2010 Indians, he was demoted to Columbus on July 27 to make room for [[Josh Tomlin]]. [[Manager (baseball)|Manager]] [[Manny Acta]] said that Brantley would soon be back in Cleveland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2010/07/cleveland_indians_promote_josh.html|title=Michael Brantley's departure expected to be a short one, says Manny Acta: Indians Insider|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> and he was recalled to Cleveland on August 6, as the Indians' [[leadoff hitter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2010/08/post_55.html|title=Michael Brantley steps right into starting lineup after being called up Friday: Cleveland Indians Insider|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>  He batted .292 for the remainder of the season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/ohio-sports-blog/index.ssf/2011/01/pm_cleveland_indians_links_37.html|title=P.M. Cleveland Indians links: Michael Brantley could impact lineup and defense this season|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> and finished the season with a .242 batting average.<ref name=turnaround>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/brantley-helping-fuel-indians-turnaround|title=Fort Pierce Central grad Michael Brantley helping fuel Indians' turnaround|work=TCP|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

In 2011, Brantley batted .266 in 114 games. He hit seven home runs, recorded 46 RBIs, and stole 13 bases.<ref name=littleleague>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/brantley-honored-for-helping-little-league|title=Cleveland Indians' Michael Brantley honored for helping Little League|work=TCP|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> After missing time due to [[tendinitis]] in his right wrist, Brantley's season ended prematurely when he required surgery on the [[hamate bone]] in his right hand in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/6903578/michael-brantley-cleveland-indians-season-wrist-injury|title=Michael Brantley of Cleveland Indians out for season with wrist injury - ESPN|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> In 2012, Brantley shifted to [[center field]] to replace the injured [[Grady Sizemore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2012/02/grady_sizemore_michael_brantle.html|title=Grady Sizemore, Michael Brantley play usual roles: Cleveland Indians spring training briefing|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> He had a career high 22-game hitting streak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/sports/brantley-just-doing-his-job-151-hitting|title=Brantley just doing his job for Cleveland Indians &#151; hitting|work=TCP|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Brantley has a patient approach to the plate that is followed by a short, compact swing. He rarely swings at the first pitch and will only do so if he has guessed the right location and type of pitch. In 2012 he was given the nickname "Dr. Smooth" by Cleveland Indians sports writer Dennis Manoloff for his smooth swing and approach at the plate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/livingston/index.ssf/2012/06/cleveland_indians_michael_bran.html|title=Cleveland Indians' Michael Brantley proving to be as smooth as a summer breeze: Bill Livingston|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> In 144 games, he batted .288 with a .348 [[on-base percentage]], .402 [[slugging percentage]], 37 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], and 60 RBIs: all setting new career highs.<ref name=hernia/>

After the 2012 season, Brantley had surgery to correct a [[sports hernia]].<ref name=hernia>{{cite web|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/10/11/michael-brantley-undergoes-sports-hernia-surgery/|title=Michael Brantley undergoes sports hernia surgery - HardballTalk|work=nbcsports.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Before the 2013 season, the Indians signed center fielder [[Michael Bourn]] as a free agent, and moved Brantley back to left field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/pluto/index.ssf/2013/03/for_the_cleveland_indians_mich.html|title=For the Cleveland Indians' Michael Brantley, the job (not the position) is the thing: Terry Pluto|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> The Indians discussed a contract extension with Brantley's representatives, but talks ended when the season began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2013/05/contract_talks_not_a_concern_f.html|title=Contract talks not a concern for Michael Brantley: Cleveland Indians Chatter|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> In August 2013, Brantley set a new Indians' franchise record for games without an [[error (baseball)|error]] by an [[outfielder]] with 213, passing [[Rocky Colavito]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2013/08/michael_brantley_sets_club_rec.html|title=Michael Brantley sets club record for errorless games by an outfielder: Cleveland Indians insider|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Brantley had a break-through season, batting .284 with 158 hits, 10 home runs, 73 RBIs, and 17 stolen bases. His errorless streak reached 245 at the end of the season.<ref name=extension>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/02/cleveland_indians_closing_in_o.html|title=Cleveland Indians, outfielder Michael Brantley agree on 4-year contract extension worth $25 million|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

Brantley was eligible for [[salary arbitration]] before the 2014 season. Rather than going through with arbitration, the Indians signed Brantley to a four year contract extension worth $25&nbsp;million, with an option for a fifth season valued at $11&nbsp;million and a $3.5&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]].<ref name=kepner/><ref name=extension/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/67629412/indians-outfielder-michael-brantley-agree-to-multiyear-contract|title=Indians, Brantley agree to multiyear contract|work=Major League Baseball|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Brantley was selected to appear in the [[2014 MLB All-Star Game]] after hitting .322 with 15 home runs and 63 RBIs during the first half of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/07/cleveland_indians_all-stars_mi.html|title=Cleveland Indians outfielder Michael Brantley selected to All-Star team; Corey Kluber part of 'Final Vote' initiative|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> On the final game of his 2014 season he picked up his 200th hit of the season making him the 18th player in Indians history to do so and first since [[Kenny Lofton]] reached the milestone in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/09/michael_brantley_remembers_som.html|title=Michael Brantley remembers someone special after reaching 200 hits for Cleveland Indians|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> After the season, Brantley won the [[Silver Slugger Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/11/michael_brantley_yan_gomes_cle.html|title=The Cleveland Indians awarded Michael Brantley, Yan Gomes long-term contracts and the two rewarded the Tribe with award-winning seasons|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref> He was named a finalist for the [[American League Most Valuable Player]] Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/11/cleveland_indians_corey_kluber_3.html|title=Cleveland Indians' Corey Kluber, Michael Brantley finalists for AL Cy Young, MVP awards|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> and finished in third place in the balloting, behind winner [[Mike Trout]] and [[V<U+00ED>ctor Mart<U+00ED>nez (baseball)|Victor Mart<U+00ED>nez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/11/cleveland_indians_michael_bran_9.html|title=Cleveland Indians' Michael Brantley "honored' to finish third in AL MVP balloting|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Brantley lives in [[Port St. Lucie, Florida]], during the baseball offseason.<ref name=turnaround/> He is married. His wife, Melissa, gave birth to their first child, daughter Mariah, in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2013/09/cleveland_indians_face_new_yor.html|title=LF Michael Brantley travels to Florida to be with expectant wife: Cleveland Indians Insider|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/05/michael_brantley_a_superstar_i.html|title=Michael Brantley, 'a superstar in the making,' reaching new heights for the Cleveland Indians|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 14, 2014}}</ref>

Brantley maintains a close relationship with his father. They speak every morning by phone to discuss his [[at bat]]s from the previous game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/the-guru-of-swing|title=The Guru of swing: Ex-major leaguer Mickey Brantley gets back to basics with local pupils|work=TCP|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Brantley's cousin, Justin, is a pitching prospect for the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2014/07/is_justin_brantley_more_like_m.html|title=Is Justin Brantley more like Michael Brantley or Pedro Martinez? -- Cleveland Indians Class A Insider (videos)|work=cleveland.com|accessdate=November 12, 2014}}</ref>

